AB  - The rapid growth of global trade has intensified the need for reliable and efficient inspection of shipping containers, as surface defects such as dents, rust, and cracks can compromise structural integrity and disrupt logistics operations. Manual inspection remains slow, labor-intensive, and inconsistent, underscoring the demand for automated solutions. This study proposes an end-to-end computer vision pipeline that integrates container detection, surface defect segmentation, and defect size estimation. A YOLOv8n detector was fine-tuned on a selfannotated dataset to accurately identify containers in video streams, while a SegFormer-B2 segmentation model was trained on both synthetic (SeaFront) and real (container-defect) datasets. Results show that although the synthetic dataset achieved strong validation accuracy, its performance degraded significantly in real-world conditions, whereas the real dataset enabled improved segmentation generalization. Post-processing techniques further enhanced mask quality by removing noise and preserving coherent defect regions. Finally, a size estimation module converted binary masks into physical defect areas under a 40 ft container assumption, producing actionable metrics such as defect count, total defective area, and maximum defect size. Experimental evaluation demonstrated that the pipeline achieved high detection accuracy $(\text{mAP} {@} 0.5=0.92)$ and robust segmentation performance ($\text{mIoU}=0.78$ on real data), validating its effectiveness in realistic port scenarios. The modular design ensures scalability, with potential extensions to multi-class segmentation, calibrated dimension mapping, and integration into smart port infrastructures. This work contributes to bridging the gap between academic advances in computer vision and practical needs in automated logistics inspection.
ER  - 

