AB  - Dynamic wireless charging (DWC) technology can significantly enhance the transportation efficiency of automated guided vehicles (AGVs) in port logistics operations. To address the challenges of integrating DWC-mode AGVs into port microgrids and improve the economics of port energy management, this study proposes a co-optimization scheduling strategy for port logistics and energy systems considering DWC-mode AGVs. First, we establish cascade logistics task models and power consumption models for quay cranes and AGVs. Second, considering the characteristics of DWC, an AGV charging model by combining DWC topology and battery model is developed. Finally, a port energy optimization scheme with multiple energy requirements is proposed, which integrates port logistics information to coordinate quay crane operation, AGV’s transportation, and charging processes. The proposed methodology aims to minimize port daily power cost while satisfying both logistics and energy demands. Numerical simulation results demonstrate that DWC load responds best to time-of-use pricing, and the proposed method achieves a cost reduction of more than 9.37% compared to plug-in AGVs.
ER  - 

