AB  - With the rapid advancement of smart port technologies, autonomous environmental perception for Intelligent Guided Vehicles (IGVs) has emerged as a pivotal challenge in achieving fully automated port operations. This paper addresses the inherent limitations of existing perception solutions and the excessive reliance of IGVs on scheduling strategies in complex and dynamic port environments. We propose a novel multi-sensor perception framework, FUSION-IGV, which integrates LiDAR and camera data for enhanced perception capabilities. To facilitate practical deployment, we provide a comprehensive toolset, including a structural design scheme, a calibration approach tailored to the unique structural characteristics of IGVs, and a multi-sensor fusion perception method. To support the development and evaluation of sensor placement strategies and perception algorithms, we also introduce PIPD: an IGV-oriented perception dataset specifically curated for port scenarios. Extensive experiments demonstrate that the proposed system significantly improves the detection and tracking performance of IGVs for both static and dynamic objects, thereby ensuring more reliable environmental perception for downstream control and decision-making processes. FUSION-IGV scores 83.03% mAP and 85.41% NDS on PIPD validation set. Even when up to three LiDAR sensors (i.e., half of the total LiDAR sensors) fail during real-world operations, the decreases in NDS and mAP remain within 2%. Moreover, our proposed image-depth prediction optimization strategy further increases both NDS and mAP by at least 2% compared to the baseline method. The effectiveness and superiority of our approach are validated through comprehensive evaluations, offering valuable insights for advancing autonomous driving technologies in smart port applications.
ER  - 

