AB  - As the core transportation carrier of global trade, container surface damage directly threatens transportation safety and efficiency, while traditional manual inspection methods are incompatible with the demands of intelligent port operations due to low efficiency and limited precision. To address this issue, this paper proposes a deep learning-based two-stage container damage detection framework to improve detection accuracy, robustness and real-time performance in complex environments. For the binary classification task of damage presence judgment, a ResNet50 model integrating positive sample self-contrastive learning and probability distribution uncertainty analysis is constructed; by enhancing the discrimination between damaged areas and background textures, the model achieves effective classification without negative samples, with a test set accuracy of 96.7% and an F1-score of 0.956. For damage localization and category recognition, an end-to-end YOLOv11 model integrated with a lightweight C2f structure, an improved PANv2 module and a decoupled detection head is designed; combined with data augmentation strategies such as random cropping and weather simulation as well as sample balance optimization, the model achieves an $\mathbf{m A P} \text{@} \mathbf{0. 5}$ of $\mathbf{8 8. 4 \%}$ and an inference speed of over $\mathbf{1 2 0}$ FPS, enabling efficient detection in scenarios with complex illumination and target occlusion. Comprehensive evaluation results show that the system obtains an overall score of 0.882, with a damage detection rate of 87.41% on 413 validation images, verifying the practical value and application potential of the proposed framework.
ER  - 

